+# Wave 2 — Visual Identity: directions & decisions
+
+*Written overnight for your morning review. Read this, then `PROGRESS.md`.*
+
+---
+
+## ⚠️ Two things to know before anything else
+
+**1. `ROADMAP.md` is not in the repo.** You asked me to read `README.md` and
+`ROADMAP.md` first and called the roadmap the plan of record. `README.md` is
+here; `ROADMAP.md` is **not committed** on `main` or the branch, and isn't in
+git history. The web container clones fresh, so a local-only uncommitted file
+never arrives. I worked from the Wave 2 guidance you wrote inline in the task
+(manuscript/plate palette, warmer+darker than neon-on-black, one signature
+element, reduced ambient motion, collapsible header). **Please `git add
+ROADMAP.md && commit` so future sessions have the real plan** — especially for
+Wave 3, where I deliberately stayed conservative without it (see PROGRESS.md).
+
+**2. Wave 1 was committed but never actually live.** "wave 1: typographic
+hierarchy + LOD" wrote its real code to root-level `app.js` and `style.css`,
+but `index.html` loads `js/app.js` and `css/style.css`. So the deployed site
+was still the pre-Wave-1 original; the Wave-1 work (four type voices, unified
+`applyLOD`, viewport culling for the pan-stutter fix, topic-label collision
+pass) sat in files the page never loaded. I promoted that code into the loaded
+paths and deleted the orphaned duplicates (separate commit, easy to revert).
+Wave 2 is built on top of a now-genuinely-live Wave 1. If you'd already spotted
+this and *intended* the root files, tell me and I'll re-point instead.
+
+---
+
+## The brief, restated
+
+Move the identity from **neon-on-black** (deep-space: blue-black radial ground,
+twinkling starfield, animated title shimmer, spinning domain rings, breathing
+field pulses, gold "energy" flowing along the bridges) to a **manuscript /
+plate** register: warmer *and* darker, a pigment palette (aged-paper golds,
+iron-gall ink, oxidised copper), **one memorable signature element**, **reduced
+ambient animation**, and a **collapsible header**.
+
+---
+
+## Three directions
+
+All three honour the brief (warm dark ground, pigment palette, reduced motion,
+collapsible header). They differ in *concept* and in the **one signature
+element** each commits to.
+
+### 1. "Iron-Gall Codex" — illuminated manuscript  ← **provisional pick**
+- **Ground:** warm vellum-dark (deep bister/sepia-black in candlelight), faint
+  static paper grain + foxing specks — *warmer and darker* than the blue-black.
+- **Palette (the 8 domains as real manuscript pigments):** iron-gall pewter
+  (Foundations — the ink everything is written in), vermilion / red-ochre
+  (Algebra), lapis lazuli (Analysis), verdigris / oxidised copper (Geometry &
+  Topology), orpiment / aged gold (Number Theory), Tyrian mulberry (Discrete),
+  turnsole violet (Probability), celadon (Order).
+- **Detail panel:** returns to **aged parchment with iron-gall ink text** — the
+  paper CSS is *already in the file*, just overridden by the Part-4 dark glass.
+  Tapping a node opens the manuscript leaf.
+- **Signature element:** **illuminated gold-leaf bridges.** The signature (★)
+  cross-domain bridges are rendered as inlaid gold leaf — a matte gilt
+  double-stroke with a faint craquelure and a soft specular sheen that appears
+  only on hover/focus — instead of neon energy flowing along a dashed line.
+  *Rationale:* the whole project argues the bridges are the point; in a codex
+  the gold is the precious, hand-laid illumination. Make the bridges the gold.
+- **Motion:** near-zero. Kill starfield twinkle, title shimmer, ring spin,
+  field pulse, and the flowing dash; keep only interaction transitions and the
+  one-time field entrance. `prefers-reduced-motion` disables even that.
+- **Why it wins:** maps one-to-one onto your exact words; biggest warmth/calm
+  swing from today; the signature element *is* the thesis; and it reuses type
+  (Spectral serif) and the paper-panel CSS already present, so it's low-risk.
+
+### 2. "Copperplate Atlas" — engraved scientific plate
+- Darker warm charcoal-taupe, like a photographed intaglio print. A tighter,
+  three-pigment identity — **oxidised copper / iron-gall ink / aged-paper
+  gold** — with the 8 domains as tinted stops along that warm axis. Nothing
+  glows: halos become hairline cross-hatch, orbs lose their bloom, edges are
+  engraved lines.
+- **Signature element:** **the platemark frame + engraved cartouche** — the
+  whole canvas bordered by a fine double platemark with rounded plate corners,
+  the title set in a ruled cartouche with a printer's fleuron (❦). The map
+  reads as one printed plate in an old atlas.
+- **Why not (yet):** most "period-accurate" and beautiful on desktop, but the
+  platemark border eats scarce mobile real estate and visually fights an
+  infinite pan/zoom canvas (a plate has edges; the web doesn't). Higher risk
+  against "don't break the navigation feel."
+
+### 3. "Astrolabe Vellum" — instrument on vellum
+- Tobacco/vellum ground; brass-and-patina palette (warm brass gold, patinated
+  copper-green, deep indigo, oxblood).
+- **Signature element:** a faint **engraved astrolabe / compass reticle** —
+  concentric degree rings and a hairline rose centred behind the map, so the 8
+  domains read as stations on a brass instrument laid on vellum.
+- **Why not (yet):** the reticle is lovely but competes with the domain layout
+  for the centre of attention, and risks reading as decoration bolted on rather
+  than identity. Strong candidate for a *later* flourish once the palette lands.
+
+---
+
+## Decision (provisional — redirect me freely)
+
+**Implementing Direction 1, "Iron-Gall Codex."** It's the most faithful to your
+words, gives the strongest calm/warmth contrast with the current look, makes
+the signature element the bridges (the project's whole argument), and reuses
+existing type + paper-panel CSS so it least endangers the working nav/panels/
+search/label systems.
+
+This is a **taste call and it is yours** — if in the morning you prefer the
+Copperplate frame or the Astrolabe reticle (or a blend), say so and I'll switch;
+the palette + motion + header work carries over to any of them, so a redirect is
+cheap. Everything below the palette is layered so individual pieces
+(gold-leaf bridges, parchment panel, paper grain) can be kept or dropped
+independently.
+
+See `PROGRESS.md` for exactly what shipped, what I skipped, and what needs you.
